# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1922-world-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1922-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The **1883 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through September 30, 1883.
[src:1922-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was the second season for the American Association (AA) and eighth season for the National League (NL).
[src:1922-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Athletics won the AA pennant, while the Boston Beaneaters won the NL pennant.
[src:1922-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] There was no postseason, although there was a canceled exhibition series between the two pennant winners.
[src:1922-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters of the National League folded.
[src:1922-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] In its place, the league enfranchised two teams: the New York Gothams and Philadelphia Quakers (today's San Francisco Giants and Philadelphia Phillies).
[src:1922-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was decided that the six-team American Association would expand to eight teams and saw the minor league New York Metropolitans join and the enfranchisement of the Columbus Buckeyes.
[src:1922-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Boston Red Caps and St.
[src:1922-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings renamed as the Boston Beaneaters and St.
[src:1922-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association and the National League, along with the Northwestern League, sign the Tripartite Agreement (also known as the National Agreement).
[src:1922-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This agreement binds the leagues to respect each other's valid player contracts as well as increasing the size of the reserve list from 6 to 11 players.
[src:1922-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The 1883 schedule consisted of 98 games for all teams in the American Association and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:1922-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 14 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:1922-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This format was unique to the 1883 season.
[src:1922-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Previously, the National League had played an 84-game schedule, with 12 games against each team being played, while a pre-expansion six-team American Association had played an 80-game schedule, with 16 games against each team being played.
[src:1922-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see the National League play a 112-game schedule (increase of 14 to 16 games each), while the American Association would expanded again, this time to twelve teams, for a 110-game schedule (of 10 games against each of the other eleven teams).
[src:1922-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all sixteen teams.
[src:1922-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] American Association would see its final day of the regular season on September 30 featuring four teams, while the National League would see its final day of the regular season on September 29, featuring all eight teams.
[src:1922-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] 6 tie games (1 in AA, 5 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:1922-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Louisville Eclipse and New York Metropolitans had one tie game each.
[src:1922-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Detroit Wolverines had three tie games each.
[src:1922-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Bisons and Philadelphia Quakers had one tie game each.
[src:1922-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Polo Grounds, home of the New York Metropolitans and Gothams, featured two baseball fields, at the southeast and southwest of the grounds.
[src:1922-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Gothams played entirely at the southeast grounds, while the Metropolitans moved alternated.
[src:1922-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The played ten games at the southeast diamond to start the season, before moving to the southwest diamond on May 30.
[src:1922-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The southwest diamond was of worse quality than the southeast diamond, so games at the southwest diamond did not last long.
[src:1922-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They played only ten games (aside from a one-off at the southeast diamond on June 13) before returning to the southeast diamond in July.
[src:1922-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They did play three more games at the southwest diamond on August 30, 31, and September 4 due to scheduling conflicts with the Gothams.
[src:1922-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Following a fire and a flood of their home at Exposition Park, the Pittsburgh Alleghenys had to move into a newly built venue, a second iteration of Exposition Park, which was built immediately south.
[src:1922-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] However, after only 17 games, they played their last game there on June 9 and returned to the first Exposition Park on June 12.
[src:1922-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The **1883 New York Gothams season** was the first professional baseball season played by the team now known as the **San Francisco Giants**.
[src:1922-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The team replaced the Troy Trojans when the National League awarded its franchise rights to John B.
[src:1922-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The team went 46–50, finishing in sixth place.
[src:1922-world-series/1884-new-york-gothams-season] The **1884 New York Gothams season** was the second season of that baseball franchise, eventually known as the San Francisco Giants.
[src:1922-world-series/1884-new-york-gothams-season] The team finished in fourth place, 22 games behind the pennant-winning Providence Grays.
[src:1922-world-series/1886-new-york-giants-season] The **1886 New York Giants season** was the franchise's fourth season.
[src:1922-world-series/1886-new-york-giants-season] The team had a record of 75–44, finishing third in the National League, 12.5 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1922-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The **1887 New York Giants season** was the franchise's fifth season.
[src:1922-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The team finished in fourth place in the National League with a record of 68–55, 10+1⁄2 games behind the Detroit Wolverines.
[src:1922-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The team amassed 415 stolen bases, the most for any team in the history of the National League.
[src:1922-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] The **1888 New York Giants season** was the franchise's sixth season.
[src:1922-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] Claiming six future Hall of Famers (Roger Connor, Mickey Welch, Buck Ewing, Tim Keefe, Jim O'Rourke, and John Montgomery Ward), the team won the National League pennant by nine games and defeated the St.
[src:1922-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] Keefe led the league in several major statistical categories, including wins, winning percentage, strikeouts, and earned run average.
[src:1922-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] The Giants beat the American Association champion St.
[src:1922-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] Louis Browns in the World Series, six games to four.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] The **1922 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball for the 1922 season.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] The 19th edition of the World Series, it matched the National League (NL) champion New York Giants against the American League (AL) champion New York Yankees.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] The Giants beat the Yankees in five games (four games to zero, with one tie) in the first Series with a permanent best-of-seven format.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] By now, the term "World Series" was being used frequently, as opposed to "World's Series".
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] The Giants held Babe Ruth in check (he batted only .118 with just one RBI) and scored just enough runs to win each of the games outside the controversial Game 2 tie.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] That game was called on account of darkness, but many thought there was sufficient light to have played some more innings (the sun was still in the sky), and there were some suspicions that one or both teams might have "allowed" the tie to happen to increase the overall gate receipts.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] Commissioner Landis was among those who was dissatisfied with the result.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] One story is that Landis asked Umpire Hildebrand, "Why the Sam Hill did you call the game?" The umpire answered, "There was a temporary haze on the field." The game decision was in the hands of the umpires, but the Commissioner's Office controlled the gate receipts.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] Landis ordered the money, more than $120,000, turned over to World War I charities, thus nullifying any impropriety.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] The tied game would turn out to be the third (and final) tied game in the history of the World Series.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] The other two tied games occurred in 1907 and 1912.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] No ties are possible under later rules, which allow for suspension of a tied game and resumption of it at a later date, as with Game 5 of the 2008 World Series.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] As of 2024, this is the last time the Giants have won the World Series at home, as their next five championships were all clinched on the road.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] This would prove to be Giants' manager John McGraw's third and final World Series win.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] The game and Series remained scoreless until the sixth inning.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] Whitey Witt tripled off of Art Nehf, then was cut down at home trying to score on a fielder's choice, but a Babe Ruth hit got the run home.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] The Yankees added another run next inning on Aaron Ward's sacrifice fly with runners on second and third.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] A three-run Giant rally in the eighth knocked out Yankee starter Bullet Joe Bush, who allowed four straight leadoff singles, the last of which to Irish Meusel scoring two. and the winning run coming off reliever Waite Hoyt on a Ross Youngs sacrifice fly.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] This was the controversial tie (see above).
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] Pitchers Bob Shawkey and Jesse Barnes went all 10 innings.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] The Giants scored all three runs in the first on Irish Meusel's three-run home run after two singles.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] The Yankees scored a run in the first on Wally Pipp's RBI single after Joe Dugan reached second on an error and another run in the fourth on Aaron Ward's home run.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] The Yankees had tied the game in the eighth on doubles by Babe Ruth and Bob Meusel, but that is the way the game ended.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] Knuckleballer Jack Scott kept the Yankees off the board.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] In the bottom of the third with runners on second and third, Frankie Frisch's sacrifice fly and Irish Meusel's RBI single scored a run each for the Giants, who added an insurance run in the seventh on Frankie Frisch's RBI single.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] This contest moved along even faster than Game 3.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] It was over in a snappy 1:41, with Giants pitcher Hugh McQuillan going the distance for a 4-3 win.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] The Yankees scored two runs in the first on back-to-back singles by Wally Pipp and Bob Meusel, but in the fifth after a leadoff single and double, Dave Bancroft's two-run single tied the game.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] After a single and groundout, Irish Meusel's groundout and Ross Youngs's RBI single scored a run each.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] Aaron Ward's home run in the seventh cut the Giants' lead to one, but the Yankees did not score after that.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] Art Nehf's five-hit pitching combined with a three-run eighth inning won the Series for the Giants.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] The Yankees scored a run in the first when Joe Dugan singled with one out, moved to second on a sacrifice bunt and scored on Wally Pipp's RBI single, but in the bottom of the second with runners on second and third, Bill Cunningham's two-run single gave the Giants the lead.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] The Yankees tied the game in the fifth on Bullet Joe Bush's RBI single after a walk and single, then took the lead on Everett Scott's sacrifice fly with runners on second and third.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] The decisive rally began with a Heinie Groh single and Frankie Frisch double.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] After an intentional walk to Ross Youngs, a two-run single by High Pockets Kelly put the Giants on top.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] The next batter, Lee King, inserted in the outfield that inning for defensive purposes, delivered an RBI single to make it 5-3, and that's how it ended.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] This was the second of three consecutive matchups between the Yankees and Giants (1921–1923) marked the only time (as of 2023), that three straight World Series featured the same two clubs.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] Brothers Bob and Irish Meusel played against each other in each of those three series, making them the first set of brothers to play against each other on opposing teams in a World Series or any Big Four championship series.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] The Giants became the second NL team to win back-to-back World Series, following the Chicago Cubs in 1907–08, and remained the last until the 1975–76 Cincinnati Reds.
[src:1922-world-series/1922-world-series] This also remains the last World Series to be won by the Giants at home, as their championships of 1933 and 1954 (for New York) and 2010, 2012 and 2014 (for San Francisco) were all clinched as the visiting team.
[src:1922-world-series/giants-season] The **1885 New York Giants season** was the franchise's third season.
[src:1922-world-series/giants-season] The team finished in second place, 2 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
